text: Just to make things clear for some of the people that are confused.  Laurie Strode is still alive because this takes place after the 1978 movie. It's a direct sequel to the original. None of the other movies matter here. They're making it that the original film had a different ending and Michael was captured that night, 40 years ago and has been in prison ever since. He is no longer Laurie's brother. That storyline started in Halloween II (1981). Also the OG actor that played 'The Shape' Nick Castle appears in only one scene. It's the window scene when Laurie first sees him.

text: I commend and appreciate the writers of this film. They have paid great attention to detail with (from what I have seen as far as trailers and sneek peeks) numerous throwbacks to the ORIGINAL John Carpenter/Debra Hill Halloween. For all of us out here old enough to remember watching this for the first time on your parents couch, the safety of mom and Dad either sitting next to you or in the kitchen making popcorn, you all know what I mean with the above statement.  I cant remember what clip I had seen recently that even had on of those wide brimmed hats in the scene. It was a nod back to the when they Show Laurie in her room after her walk home with Annie And Linda. You will notice the SAME hat hanging on her wall that is in one of the scenes for the 2018 Halloween. This is gonna be one hell of a film folks!!  Buckle up as we are transported back to where it allllllllll began and brought up to present day. Happy Halloween everyone! 🎃🎃🎃🎃🎃 "DEATH HAS COME TO YOUR LITTLE TOWN SHERIFF!"

text: Fucking AWESOME!! Excuse my profanity. I just got through my 2nd viewing of this new trailer. SO PUMPED for next month!!! Laurie Strode ain't fucking around this time. It be cool if, right before she kills Michael ( if she kills him, that is) Laurie says to him, "Trick or Treat, Motherfucker!" As a reference to the shit-show that was Resurrection. Then again, that doesn't seem like something Laurie would say, even to Michael Myers.  Also, something I still don't get is why would Myers still be after Laurie after 40 YEARS. I get that, in the original, Michael most likely targeted her because she was the first person he saw, and something about her captivated him. Ok. That's fine. But after forty years of incarceration at Smith's Grove, Michael escapes and thinks, " Hm, who should I kill first? Oh, I know! How about that Strode girl I failed to kill 4 decades ago! Despite the fact that there are hundreds of other residents in Haddonfield that I could butcher and kill, I'll obsess over this one person!" Because THAT totally makes sense. With H2 and all other sequels being non-canon, Michael's obsession over Laurie in this Halloween film is unnecessary! Why would he fixate on one person, in a town of possible HUNDREDS, for 40 years? How does he even still remember who she is, for God's sake. He's spent the last 40 YEARS behind bars. SURELY there were other things on his mind. Sorry for the rant, just needed to get that off my chest.

text: I see the scene with the old lady in the kitchen, where Michael grabs the knife, less of a 'nod' to part II, but more as picking up where part II started, sort of. Think of Evil Dead 1 and 2. At the end of Evil Dead 1, the demon gets Ash. Instead of 'retelling' Evil Dead 1 verbatim at the beginning of Part 2, they 'retold' it by slimming down his friends, girlfriend, and sister, to just his girlfriend. AFTER Ash wakes up from the puddle possessed, that's where the retelling of Part 1 ends, and Part 2 begins.

text: 2018 is just BLOWING my mind, as a loyal horror fan. I mean, what monumental achievements we have. This year will go down in horror history as the year of the triple threat -- with Halloween (2018), Hereditary and A Quiet Place earning their place among the classics. 2018 has seen some of the most groundbreaking horror films since the turn of the millenium. The bold, beautiful and heart-pounding What Keeps You Alive deserves an honorable mention. The horror genre hasn't gotten this much glory since the days of all the original classics, as well as '96 when the original Scream brought the genre back from the dead. We've had a few more fleeting landmarks with The Sixth Sense, The Ring, The Descent, The Conjuring, but this year is truly unparalleled.  Hereditary & A Quiet Place are even being considered for OSCARS this year. Thanks to Get Out's nomination last year for paving the way. I honestly think Toni Collette has a shot at winning best actress, with Emily Blunt a close second (her portrayal of attempting to deliver a baby in silence was absolutely incredible).  Just to re-cap all of this: the horror films to see this year are A Quiet Place, Hereditary, What Keeps You Alive, and Halloween (2018). Annihilation was also INCREDIBLE, but more sci-fi with elements of horror blended in. Steven Soderbergh's Unsane also deserves a mention: a fantastic psychological thriller with an unforgettable performance from Claire Foy.

text: This movie doesn't capture the essence of the original at all. Michael Myers was depicted as a borderline supernatural entity, always shrouded in darkness to where you couldn't get a good look at him until the end. His actions bordered between a senseless mental patient and a calculated, malicious, truly evil being, which made him scary because you couldn't get a handle on what he was capable of. The way he's over-exposed in this new film, walking around slaughtering random people just makes this feel like Friday the 13th.

text: I think slashers are ready to actually scare people again.  We haven't had a legitimately good one that hit the mainstream since 1996 Scream, so this entire generation isn't used to slasher movies like people who grew up in the 80s and 90s.  This generation is used to ghost and haunted house type horror movies.  I think the atmosphere, the tone, the tension, and the realistic brutality of this film is going to have the younger people wetting their pants, and if it can get the same reaction it got in 1978, then that is just awesome.

text: I don't think this remake will "make" it.  Back in the 1970's and 1980's when it was new, people were more WILLING to believe and let themselves be scared.  40 years later, today, we're a tougher crowd.  Michael Myers is JUST a psychopath.  He is NOT supernatural.  He can be killed just as easily as any other human.  We AREN'T WILLING to believe that guys with guns are so unaware of their surroundings that Michael Myers can just walk up behind them and kill them.  We AREN'T WILLING to believe that Myers can magically appear inside a locked house without making any noise.  Michael Myers is human and needs blood to survive.  If I met him, he would be filled with so many holes that he would bleed out in five seconds.  Then, I would take his head off.  Try to come back from THAT, Michael.

text: When I first saw this title, I thought it was another Rob Zombie film and wasn’t too excited.  Then I heard the woman’s narration & thought to myself, “That can’t be Jamie Lee Curtis. Besides, I’m sure she’s sick of doing all these sequels.”  But sure enough, it is her. I also noticed veteran actor Will Patton as the sheriff.  Add to that, some pretty suspenseful scenes that look reminiscent of the original and we might just have a winner here, folks.  👍  So definitely looking forward to this one.

text: Ok; maybe I am reading too much into it, maybe not. It is a fact that political views are often thrown into movies now a days, whether it be a subtle point or blatantly "in your face" one. I happen to think (just from the trailer) that a subtle one is being highlighted here. I love the Halloween movies, I truly do. I just hope that it is not what appears to be as far as the political "push". What push? The firearms used. Notice that Laurie (a civilian) uses a lever action & a revolver, but the police are using a semi-auto. It appears that "they" want to push the point that civilians should not have what the left calls "weapons of war/battle" and that only military & police should have semi-autos. Call me what you like, but from the trailer; it does appear odd.

I use to love the slasher genre but know I crave substance over action. Just my opinion.

text: I like how human Michael's movements are! His walk sort of reminds me of child Michael's walk. To me, it adds a creepy factor knowing the psycho is human with emotion and motivation. I know it would kill the classic walk, but to see him run with intent would be terrifying! Not a full sprint or a jog... but a purposeful stride of even 3-5 steps ending with a firm grasp at the intended target! Not a lot of running, still stay true to the original walk. But when after Laurie, to show urgency and hatred could really add to the evilness of Michael's psychology.

text: I still prefer the old original "Halloween" that I saw as a teenager. It scared the living daylights out of me. What made it great besides the great casting of Jamie Lee Curtis and Donald Pleasance as the psych doc was that was the first suspense/horror movie made set on Halloween and involving a catatonic sociopath who escapes from an insane asylum to become the real life boogyman. Plus, adding that simple few music notes made it complete. I don't find blood and gore the least bit scary. Those movies have no imagination and anyone can go looping off heads with a chainsaw but to me it's having a good storyline, actors and it's the suspense of what might happen and the buildup to it that made the original Halloween movie at the edge of my seat screaming for Laurie to hurry up and run faster or the uncertainty of where he's gonna pop up next. That scene when she hides in the closet and Michael Myers is there in the room and I'm going No! No!.... I still hail [it] the original Halloween still today as the most scariest movies I've seen. The sequels never measured up to the first as far as I'm concerned. The 1st was the best and can't be outdone.

text: The suspense in the original which came out before Friday the 13th, and the notion that all slasher antagonists were juggernauts ever existed, was built  on the idea that he looked human, but acted less humane than humanity could imagine. He sauntered like a zombie, waited in the shadows, but for the 70's still was able to stay undetected in suburban areas. He was able to stand roughly half a block from his victims in daylight, and not get spotted. It's disturbingly nice to see that revisited.  I think the premise of him walking down the street initially highlights how society changes after forty years and how similar society stays. There's more horror in the news than there is in folklore, and the only person in Haddonfield that understands the presence of danger is Laurie. The kids are too young to have ever learned about Michael, so they probably thought he was just a parent or adult trick or treater.   After forty years without incident, residents of Haddonfield likely got comfortable in their sense of safety and disregarded the horrors of the past, and as they say: "Those that forget history are doomed to repeat it."  Michael likely felt this, as well as a sense of nostalgia walking through the town once again. Like a kid in a candy store, he was trying to pick out what was first. What made Michael scary in the original film was that he was patient, methodical, ridiculously strong, and stoic.  Having retconned the sequels, and establishing this as a stand-alone "what if" scenario gives the makers of this Halloween freedom to say "this is what COULD happen if we remove the mythology from the series and strip it back to basics."   No supernatural elements, no sibling issues, no undead carbon copy killer: They left the methodical monster from the original film alone in an asylum with 40 years to plan ahead and reflect on his mistakes.  And on the tail side of the coin, they left the sole survivor to plan ahead and remember for forty years what she survived. Laurie waited forty years, as life and history slowly desensitized itself to what happened so much that the teenagers can nonchalantly talk about what happened like a childhood camping trip or a story their grandparents told them about their hey day.   All the while, she did everything she could to try and ensure she'd be the hunter and not the prey this time. She armed herself, made contingencies for her family, disregarded her reputation in town and relegated herself to the town crazy lady to ensure her and hers were safe.   I'm liking the direction this is headed. Here's hoping for a great story.  Come October, we'll have the answer to that "What If" question.   Fingers crossed!

text: Okay. So. Michael was five years old when he killed his sister in the beginning of the original Halloween movie. However, the focus of the movie is his baby sister, Laurie, when she's a senior in high school. Roughly, let's give or take a 15 year time span. If Laurie was 17 in 1978, that would mean Michael would have been 5 years old in 1963, making him at least 22 during the focus of the film. If what Laurie had said is true, "forty years ago," that would imply Michael being at least 62 years old. I'm beginning to think less of how the Halloween series as a horror movie series and see it as a documentary on how bad our government is. Either Michael is Saddam and has been hiding in a cave for forty years and only peeks his head out like a groundhog once a year or there are some plot holes to this movie that have already come to light. Yes, there are a lot of very fit and healthy 60 year old men out there BUT that takes a lot of good dieting and exercise. Hypothetically, let's say Michael was in the penitentiary for the last forty years, convicts do not get fed the necessary means to obtain such a diet. Now, let's say Michael lived in the wild for the last 40 years, that would mean Michael would be even more skilled at hunting than Ted Nugent. Lets give Michael the benefit of the doubt and say he is this skilled hunter and has been surviving off the land all this time. Say he mastered hunting, which there isn't a whole lot of hunting to do in Illinois because it is mostly farmland, it would be next to impossible for him to never get caught, or more importantly, surviving the winters as long as he apparently has. My point is, it doesn't take a genius to realize the plot holes.

The only way to get people to be scared of anything nowadays is to put them in those situations (I don't mean actually getting a knife and mass murdering people). The way it works is a group of people is placed in random locations in the town and their objective is to find the key to the gate in order to escape.  The killers' job is to basically scare the people shitless and capture them.  Once you are captured, you lose.  There are no lights, the only light source are the people's flashlights and the killer has night vision goggles.

author: Christian Rivera

text: Jesus, could they have shamelessly referenced any more elements from the past films? This is basically Halloween H40: 40 Years Later, incorporating elements of Halloween II (Michael stalking the residents of Haddonfield, killing them and going about undetected on Halloween night), the fucking kid that runs into Michael in the original Halloween scene is LITERALLY ripped off, Laurie being cautious about Michael's inevitable escape/return, the bathroom scene, Michael gaining his ensemble in the same fashion as Halloween 4, it's incredible.  Still looks cool though, be nice to see what the FUCK the story's going to be and what everyone is creating such praise for when this story and franchise has been done to death to the point it's only source of revival is through omission of the sequels and starting anew with a different timeline or a reboot altogether.  Shame they didn't have the balls to try and pick up after that bullshit cliffhanger in Halloween: Resurrection, or Halloween 6, which, practically would've been impossible, but I would've had much more respect for them trying to continue instead of negating the elements of the story constantly and throwing out what was made to have an excuse to rewrite a story that had several dead ends.  Don't you love how they undermine the suspense of the original's ending by flat out making it clear that Michael didn't get far and was captured the same night?   Wouldn't the original ending to Carpenter's classic be so much more scary and meaningful if Michael's fate was left ambiguous, instead of being spoon-fed this contrived device to have him recaptured when, by all extents of his capabilities and actions in the first film, should NOT have been possible in the first place?

text: The theme song was made in 3 days. The film shot by students straight outta college. Micheal myers was played by 4 people. One a random friend, another the script writer, the stunt man, and the set designer. The actors all wore their own clothes because the film had that low of a budget. The long shot of the house at the beginning didn't have enough lighting so the crew had to run throughout the house to change the lighting in the rooms before the camera came. Out of it all, came the first Halloween, one of Americas most beloved classic horror films

text: Okay, there's something I feel needs to be addressed about the upcoming Halloween film. Since this new movie is completely forgoing all the events that transpired after the 1st film, and Myers has been wallowing in the sanatarium for 40 years, unable to cause anyone, any harm; not the least of which Laurie Strode-why then, did Strode tell the sheriff she had been hoping and waiting for Michael to escape? Why would she say that? What would make her think he would ever be able to escape? Supposedly, according to the (new)lore/timeline, none of those other sequels ever took place. So, the continuity is all out of whack. Am I missing something? Can someone, anyone shed some light on to this and resolve this discrepancy, because it makes virtually no sense. Laurie Strode would have no reason to believe Michael was planning on coming after her. WTF, is she a friggin' psychic? Remember, he only went after her one time.  Not twice or 3 times. Sorry but this really bugged me.

text: Michaels Character, the Emotionless mask, the legendary John Carpenter  score, small flat tire swing type of town with 5 Police Officers, the quietness of of the movie .... are all reasons why the original Halloween is the best horror movie of all time. I was always a die hard fan of Halloween and I always watched the sequels. As a kid I loves them but now realize just how pointless and dumb they are. Honestly Michael Myers himself is the only cool part of them. So if a sequel to the original needs to come out 40 years later to try and rectify the simple yet brilliant story that John Carpenter told ... so be it.

text: I've saw this movie's ending in Toronto. I liked it. It made me do some thinking. They can either go with the Halloween 3 or Halloween (whatever year) idea or Hellraiser vs Michael Myers idea because 1 this movie can confirm Myers being fully immortal. 2 It can explain his childhood and why he acts the way he acts,etc and lastly 3 it's far more important than Michael vs Jason. Why I said those 3? for those who don't know.. here's why! this movie can confirm Myers being fully immortal because Judith Myers (Michael's sister) she could've found the puzzle box sitting around somewhere, picked it up, and gave it to Michael to play with or whatever then Michael plays with it, finds out a way to open it and Hellraiser and the cenobites appear sending Michael to hell and they curse him to kill forever or once he opens it, they tear his soul apart. then they do what they did to Hellraiser and make Michael immortal in hell, then Michael becomes immortal and blames his family for his death or Judith. Which explains why he killed her (which is justifiable.) or is just back for revenge and wants to take his anger out on anyone he see's. They can go with any of those directions. It's more important than Michael vs Jason because this movie confirms Michael being immortal rather than being mortal. Then Michael could actually stand a chance against Zombie Voorhees from ft13th 6-9, Jason X, and Freddy vs Jason. Matter and fact Michael might actually win against Jason if he's immortal. I mean they're both immortal but if Michael's immortal and facing Jason, not to mention Michael HAS intelligence! (Jason does as well but doesn't use it often and isn't as intelligent as Michael). Michael would win.  ALSO Hellraiser vs Michael Myers the winner should be Michael Myers setting up Michael  vs Jason afterwards.  I don't think it's too late for a Hellraiser vs Michael Myers movie Doug could prob get back in shape for the movie.

text: The 1978 original is one of the best horror movies ever made. It's easy to create violence on the screen, but it's hard to do it well. In this case Carpenter does an amazing job of it. One of the things that is great is how he portrays the victims. They're all ordinary, everyday people -- nobody's supposed to be the star and have a big scene and win a Golden Globe or an Academy Award. The performances are all the better because of that; the movie's a slice of typical Americana that is carefully constructed before the monster enters the scene. It doesn't need over the top scenes of blood and gore to frighten us. Instead it uses the most terrifying weapon available to us......….our own thoughts. Not to mention the intro music is absolutely brilliant. It sends a chill down your spine and sets the tone for the movie right off the bat. Hoping for the best with this remake.

text: Can't wait to see this one...He's coming home! This looks like it was a Halloween sequel made by folks who are fans of the original. Rob Zombie did good with the first and bombed on the second. I see this one doing the second coming of Michael Meyers the justice it deserves. I like the more human Michael and his more random victims. Also...the additional violence that he displays. Michael dropping the teeth of a victim into the bathroom stall gave me chills. In H20 he only takes a purse and leaves the bathroom. Michael is an insane, rage filled killing machine and he has been waiting 40 years to get out and do his thing. Well done Danny McBride and Co. I hope the trailer is only the beginning.

text: This is the worst way to tell the story. To completely disregard every movie that came after the original is stupid!  They tried it with H20/Resurrection and they were the worst movies in the franchise! We're just suppose to pretend that Michael Myers sat around doing nothin and it took him FOUR DECADES TO ESCAPE!!!!??? The best way to pay homage to the other movies was to NOT COMPLETELY IGNORE THEM! The trilogy with Jamie (Danielle Harris) was the best part of the entire series! All they had to do was continue from there. It would've been perfect to continue from the end of Halloween IV! Easily explain Dr. Loomis' absence by him dying of a heart attack after witnessing Jamie attempt to murder her foster parent, thus fearing the whole saga happening all over again! Finally having "Jamie" and "Laurie" together on screen giving fans exactly what they want for the very last movie! Use them both to tie up all the loose ends, while using their mother/daughter dynamic to tell a story within a story. Then, teaming up to kill Michael  and finishing the series once and for all leaving no room for anymore questions! But actually having Laurie die in battle with Michael at the end, having Jamie be the lone survivor, to give the finale a good twist...And what about Dr. Loomis'(Donald Pleasance's) legacy? Everything he sacrificed to kill Michael, just gets erased from history, and becomes "rumors and made up stories" throughout the years? Its ridiculous! This is my favorite horror series ever but these sequels and remakes are poorly put together and have ruined a great franchise!

text: So this movie is basically going to narrow the Halloween duology down to what kind of *Laurie Strode vs Michael Myers* ending a person prefers.  Do you want the ending, where Laurie (for good reasons) spends the entire movie being so hysterically loud, and screaming like she’s trying to make her audience regret they have the ability to hear, meanwhile she tries to escape Michael at such a slow pase where it looks like she could care less whether or not he ends up killing her? Then pick: *Halloween II* (1981)! or... Do you want the ending, where Laurie (after years of training) is ready to fight for the sake of her family, and for the sake of herself to finally end the years of trauma that, that beanheaded-Michael has caused her, inside a movie where the screenplay and direction actually looks really damn fckin good! A movie where the death scenes look as terrifying and haunting as they did in the original movie. And a movie that seems to highlight why Michael is such an iconic antagonist? Then pick: *Halloween* (2018)!  Nonetheless I’m excited asf! And I kinda forgot, why I wanted to write this, but now that I’ve done it, I sure as hell am going to publish it.. If Michael doesn’t kill you, the length of this message probably will. I don’t even wanna read this twice, damn.
author: Mark

text: Jamie Lee Curtis is a strong, sometimes hysterical, gun control advocate, as evidenced by her tweets on this subject. Is she just another Hollywood hypocrite?   And for those who are saying this Jamie Lee Curtis role has nothing to do with the real world, let me point to several recent interviews with Jamie Lee Curtis talking about the new film. On "the View" she said: “I know it’s a slasher movie…but it actually is about something.” She continued, “It is fiction. I’m not saying it happened to me. It happened to Laurie Strode in the movies and here we are having a conversation, a global conversation about trauma…Christine Ford said this affected her…” Curtis went on to connect it to other incidents of trauma including a home invasion robbery and the women “drugged and raped” by Bill Cosby. “The heroine of Halloween is a woman who suffered a trauma when she was 17, like Dr. Ford when she was 17 and it changed and shaped her life. And now she is taking back the power.” In other words, it’s fiction but it connects to something real. That’s her pitch.  So here’s my question and it’s a sincere one: If the trauma is meant to connect to current, real trauma people are talking about, why doesn’t the specific response (gun ownership) also connect to specific issues we’re talking about at this moment. Curtis can certainly say the trauma is a real thing but the guns are just fantasy device, but why? I mean, real women in the world carry and own guns for exactly this reason. They don’t want to be traumatized by some crazed stalker, which is kind of the whole plot of Halloween and I guess this new movie as well. Does Curtis believe that owning a gun in real life is a legitimate way for women to take back the power? I think it’s a fair question.  Some say that maybe Curtis felt trapped into this because it’s her most famous role and guns were just part of the package. But that’s not true. Curtis never had a gun in the original film, only Dr. Loomis (played by Donald Pleasence) had one. And by the way, he saved her life with it at the end of the first movie. She literally would be dead if not for that revolver!!!  I agree that’s actually a positive, empowering message. I’m all for women owning guns (assuming they learn how to use them safely) because men are bigger and some of them are creeps. So, great, I like this story the film is telling. But I still think it’s not one that sits as easily with Curtis’ gun control campaigning...  More here: https://hotair.com/archives/2018/10/10/jamie-lee-curtis-making-movies-featuring-guns/

text: I grew up on Halloween, coming out on my 8th birthday. It literally scared the shit out of me for years decades and that of my entire generation. Back then you could be left at home alone at night without your parents or a baby sitter and it was totally legal, creepy doors, shutters, storms, backyards, garages, real Halloween nights with getting apples being laced with razor blades, howling winds, real serial killers every night on the news, real killings, real kids living this, so Halloween is a truly special film series that speaks to an entire Generation of audiences, shaping them. Terrifying them, giving them nightmares and memories forever and wherever. There was nothing but horror film after horror film from the late 70's thru the 80's because of this movie. It had a huge effect on millions of kids and I think it shaped an entire generation unlike the Millennials of today who had none of that and are so f'd up today.  This was a great movie, great filmmaking, great acting, great horror scenes. Go see it. I know millions of Gen X'rs will for sure!!!  Can't wait to see it again. Definitely had a hard time sleeping afterwards, the images and violence is so incredibly real and I've worked with and cut up dead bodies in autopsies and surgeries and seen and worked with tons of blood, brains, and guts and real fucking real scary real viciously violent evil psychos in real life. Every scene is very authentic, creepy AF and simply awesome all around.  Can't wait for the sequel. Just gets better and better. Turned my interest in all the old horror films that I avoided because this one in 1978 scared me shitless, turned it on wide open.  All the classic Horror films are great and this series is the best!  This movie is more about the generational  trauma that haunts victims. People who don't understand that and are quite immature are the ones who didn't like it. It's great. It's real and it's scary and it's fulfilling for anyone who has lived a full life, especially well-developed women. The losers who didn't like it wouldn't know a good movie if they saw one and are big infantile boys still wearing diapers and thumb-sucking.  You want to know what's scary? Talk to trauma victims. Talk to gunners from OEF/OIF who are haunted by the ghosts of the Iraqi's they killed. Talk to Vietnam Vets who were mole rats and who can kill you with their bare hands. Talk to psychos who you can see nothing but pure menacing coldness and evil in their eyes. The way they move and stab you. This movie is all that and is fucking real, fucking poignant and simply the best, full circle. Wait til you live some of these scenes in real life and you will know what disturbing and scary is. This movie won't get your adrenaline flowing externally but will disturb you internally. It's like a rounded out, smoothed out, shaved down Halloween targeting much bigger audiences. It's the haunting imagery afterwards that gets you WHEN you LEAVE the theater.  Great movie! Go see it. The theater was fully packed and that has happened in three decades.

text: It wasn’t bad. I feel it could have been a bit better, but it was better than any of the other sequels by far. This movie is filled with suspense, scares, and even comedy. The theater room was literally filled with laughter during a brutal murder of a young blonde teenage girl. How could just a tragic and horrific thing be funny? Well, I won’t tell you why it’s funny, but just know you will laugh while this girl is being sliced and diced by Michael Myers. But the comedy was refreshing. It actually fit in well. And I don’t think I saw any nudity other than a clip from the original movie that was played, which was the scene where Michael killed his sister when he was a young lad. They don’t waste screen time on boob shots or sex scenes. It is particularly interesting when you get to spend quite a bit of time watching from Michael’s perspective. You see how he gets in peoples homes without them noticing him, etc. And I sincerely felt sad for Michael Myers at the end of the movie. To keep me from tearing up for Michael, I had to remind myself several times that he murdered a bunch of people and he only got what he deserved.

text: Not a good movie.  A lot of unlikable scenes.  Didn't feel like true Michael Myers from first 2.  The first two Halloween movies are the only ones that are good. Especially the 1st one.   This new 2018 one sucked.  Halloween H20 is a good watch.  Part 6 is a fun watch.  The rest of them are garbage.  Most after the first 2 try to copy other movies.  H20 copied the vibe from Scream.  4 and 5 copied friday the 13th films.  Resurrection copied the reality tv camera style like blair witch project.  And this 2018 director/writer tried to copy Goodfellas (tracking shot) and texas chainsaw massacre (out of sync kill, shutting the door hard etc.) as well as paying tribute to first halloween but it sucked and didn't do the first 1 and better sequel justice.

And the doctor part, how stupid and uncalled for??  Should of kept the doctor out of it!  The first movie was so dark and chilling, now they are not any better than any of the other remade ones!!!!  Also if they keep this going again, they are just stupid!!!  Considering the fact that the last how many Halloween movies didnt happen according to this one, so why would they want to start doing it again with Myers chasing Jamies Grand daughter again????  Just as well have kept the others in play then!!

It would be nice to hear from the creators of this film if they ever did have the intention of including the events Halloween 2 in this movie and if so what was their idea.
